1
00:00:01,651 --> 00:00:03,112
Four Noble Truths.

2
00:00:04,535 --> 00:00:10,003
Soon after his enlightenment, the Buddha decided to teach others how to follow his lead.

3
00:00:10,603 --> 00:00:19,536
He first sought out his earlier spiritual companions and told them of four observations that had led him to liberation.

4
00:00:20,978 --> 00:00:28,309
These later became known as the Four Noble Truths and are the cornerstone for all schools of Buddhism.

5
00:00:29,510 --> 00:00:31,253
All truths concern Dukkha,

6
00:00:31,856 --> 00:00:40,024
a Pali word usually translated as suffering or sometimes a stress, distress or unsatisfactoriness.

7
00:00:41,426 --> 00:00:50,433
Dukkha spans the full range of negativity we experience from minor irritations to rage, terror and despair.

8
00:00:51,634 --> 00:00:59,381
The Buddha told his companions that liberation involved seeing for himself that this is suffering.

9
00:00:59,881 --> 00:01:01,863
This is the cause of suffering.

10
00:01:02,317 --> 00:01:04,760
This is the cessation of suffering.

11
00:01:05,459 --> 00:01:09,745
This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.

12
00:01:11,186 --> 00:01:14,689
The word this refers to something close at hand.

13
00:01:15,611 --> 00:01:18,114
It's not an abstract idea to think about.

14
00:01:18,655 --> 00:01:23,019
It's something we can see or feel or experience here and now.

15
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:28,105
This cup, this foot, this thought.

16
00:01:29,114 --> 00:01:32,498
We learn the Four Noble Truths from direct experience.

17
00:01:33,259 --> 00:01:47,817
We feel how suffering feels, discover what causes it, realize that suffering can stop, let that guide us along the path that reduces suffering, brings it eventually to a complete end.

18
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:58,632
As we learn the Four Noble Truths, we move from delusion to an understanding of what causes suffering, what makes us happy.

19
00:01:59,572 --> 00:02:04,218
We often think of understanding as a purely intellectual, rational process.

20
00:02:04,838 --> 00:02:15,451
We think we should only have to learn the Dhamma once and then have this as a skill we can call upon any time in the same way as we learned how to drive or fix a puncture.

21
00:02:16,573 --> 00:02:20,798
But the understanding we need for liberation is not purely cognitive.

22
00:02:21,399 --> 00:02:26,104
We have to take the Dhamma fully to heart until we're fully liberated

23
00:02:26,405 --> 00:02:34,913
we'll be continually relearning the Four Noble Truths, feeling the dukkha in experience, searching for the cause.

24
00:02:37,576 --> 00:02:41,640
The First Noble Truth is basically the Buddha's definition of dukkha.

25
00:02:42,401 --> 00:02:49,528
Birth is dukkha, old age and death are dukkha, sorrow, lamentations and despair are dukkha.

26
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:53,052
Being connected to what one dislikes is dukkha.

27
00:02:53,522 --> 00:03:00,334
and being separated from what one likes is dukkha and not getting what one wants is dukkha.

28
00:03:00,354 --> 00:03:04,118
In short, the five aggregates of clinging are dukkha.

29
00:03:05,260 --> 00:03:06,263
Birth is dukkha.

30
00:03:06,782 --> 00:03:14,675
We usually think of birth as joyous, but in fact, physical birth is a painful and perilous process for mother and baby.

31
00:03:15,717 --> 00:03:20,104
It's when both are pronounced safe and well that the joy arises.

32
00:03:20,539 --> 00:03:23,544
Before that, it's touch and go between hope and fear.

33
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:29,030
We also get a flavour of this when we look closely at the start of any process.

34
00:03:29,670 --> 00:03:30,991
A new job, for example.

35
00:03:32,133 --> 00:03:48,993
Again, we think of it as good news, something to celebrate, but there is that awkward first day in the office, not knowing anyone or where things are kept or how not to be a nuisance, having to learn a lot of new procedures, watching our P's and Q's,

36
00:03:50,002 --> 00:03:52,006
taking care to make a good impression.

37
00:03:52,806 --> 00:03:55,651
It's not something we would want to do every day of our lives.

38
00:03:55,790 --> 00:03:57,152
It would be too stressful.

39
00:03:58,153 --> 00:04:00,576
Now, some of us love new beginnings.

40
00:04:00,897 --> 00:04:02,400
There's a sense of potential.

41
00:04:02,939 --> 00:04:03,921
Anything could happen.

42
00:04:04,222 --> 00:04:15,236
If we're the optimistic type, we project all kinds of wonders into whatever it is, a new job, a new partner, the start of a holiday, the first few hours of a retreat.

43
00:04:15,978 --> 00:04:17,920
Everything is going to be perfect.

44
00:04:18,040 --> 00:04:19,723
We'd be enlightened in no time.

45
00:04:20,665 --> 00:04:25,589
This kind of over-the-top optimism is one manifestation of delusion.

46
00:04:26,209 --> 00:04:31,314
The truth is that we don't know what's going to happen, whether things will turn out well or not.

47
00:04:31,855 --> 00:04:41,504
And that experience of not knowing is so uncomfortable for us that we concoct lovely fantasies rather than feel the experience.

48
00:04:41,526 --> 00:04:49,153
But after a year or maybe only a week of the new job, new partner, perhaps only a day or two into the holiday or retreat,

49
00:04:49,689 --> 00:04:55,858
we realise that it's not all a bed of roses, that the reality doesn't match up to the fantasies.

50
00:04:56,738 --> 00:05:05,370
And if things do turn out well and our expectations are all met or even exceeded, there will be a time when it all comes asunder.

51
00:05:05,990 --> 00:05:08,374
We'll someday have to retire from the job.

52
00:05:08,754 --> 00:05:12,560
The holiday will come to an end, as will the retreat.

53
00:05:13,161 --> 00:05:17,165
Our partner will die or else we will die and leave it all behind.

54
00:05:17,584 --> 00:05:21,490
the job, the holiday, the loving relationships, all our retreats.

55
00:05:22,452 --> 00:05:24,956
Everything we know ends at death.

56
00:05:26,278 --> 00:05:29,843
Death is the second example of dukkha which the Buddha gives.

57
00:05:30,826 --> 00:05:33,108
Our own physical death is indeed the big one.

58
00:05:34,250 --> 00:05:39,298
Unless we can say goodbye to all we hold dear, death will surely be a time of anguish.

59
00:05:39,699 --> 00:05:45,769
We can practice our goodbyes by paying attention to the ending of any activity or event.

60
00:05:46,406 --> 00:05:49,391
These can all be seen as mini-deaths.

61
00:05:51,293 --> 00:06:06,531
We often make light of them by thinking ahead to what's to come, but that won't be an option at our real death, so we might as well pause at endings now, acknowledge that the holiday or the party or some particular task is coming to an end.

62
00:06:07,552 --> 00:06:12,298
There may be relief, a sense of something accomplished, a job well done.

63
00:06:12,338 --> 00:06:13,899
The sentiments

64
00:06:14,098 --> 00:06:15,199
is to be treasured.

65
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:20,064
If we can feel the same way at our own death, it will be a great gift.

66
00:06:21,225 --> 00:06:26,492
We might also detect grief, knowing that something we were enjoying is now stopping.

67
00:06:27,353 --> 00:06:35,600
There can be a surprising amount of grief, even at the close of relatively trivial events, when we pay close attention.

68
00:06:36,783 --> 00:06:43,009
On retreat at Gaia House one time, I was following the usual Mahasi, single biscuit in the evening practice,

69
00:06:43,867 --> 00:06:47,711
but all the while envying the other retreatments, their bowls of soup.

70
00:06:49,132 --> 00:06:53,896
I looked forward so much to the final day when I could have that evening treat.

71
00:06:54,577 --> 00:06:57,880
Sure enough, the day came and the soup was delicious.

72
00:06:58,422 --> 00:07:03,906
I savoured every mouthful until I noticed that the bowl was no longer even half full.

73
00:07:04,608 --> 00:07:08,091
A big wave of misery emerged and got stuck in my throat.

74
00:07:08,911 --> 00:07:11,814
It was my first real recognition of the truth.

75
00:07:12,367 --> 00:07:14,370
that all pleasures come to an end.

76
00:07:15,232 --> 00:07:20,639
I got the Buddha's full whammy of sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair.

77
00:07:21,341 --> 00:07:27,129
I couldn't even finish my treasured bowl of soup, but went to my room and howled in misery.

78
00:07:29,273 --> 00:07:38,747
Having realised the emotional impact of delusive over-expectations, I never built such high expectations out of sense pleasures again.

79
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:43,035
This is the benefit of paying attention to ending.

80
00:07:43,755 --> 00:07:56,596
We move from delusion to wisdom, and instead of being continually disappointed by the world, by other people, we grow to accept that neither the world or other people can bring us lasting happiness.

81
00:07:57,858 --> 00:08:06,029
We grow more forgiving of our own and others' limitations, more appreciative of whatever does happen to go right.

82
00:08:07,711 --> 00:08:09,595
The Buddha summarizes dukkha

83
00:08:09,997 --> 00:08:13,341
by saying the five aggregates of clinging are dukkha.

84
00:08:14,043 --> 00:08:19,911
These aggregates of clinging are what we mistakenly assume to be our true selves.

85
00:08:20,793 --> 00:08:30,127
That essential element of me, which has been with me since birth and will remain with me to death and perhaps hereafter.

86
00:08:30,146 --> 00:08:34,553
In Christianity, we would call this our soul.

87
00:08:35,235 --> 00:08:38,620
The Buddha searched ardently for his essence and on the way,

88
00:08:38,988 --> 00:08:43,533
discovered a series of false identities which ensnared him in Dukkha.

89
00:08:44,115 --> 00:08:49,842
He used this discovery as the basis for his teaching on anatta, or not self.

90
00:08:50,744 --> 00:08:57,092
To find our true essence, we must first see through all the false identities we assume.

91
00:08:57,133 --> 00:09:05,183
At times we identify with the body, feeling proud of our strength or beauty, ashamed of our pimples and wrinkles.

92
00:09:06,004 --> 00:09:07,307
This is Dukkha.

93
00:09:07,927 --> 00:09:15,099
The Buddha points out that such inconstancy is not worthy of being thought of as an essential part of our identity.

94
00:09:16,340 --> 00:09:23,571
At other times, we identify with our feelings, get deeply wounded when these are hurt, yet more dukkha.

95
00:09:24,111 --> 00:09:32,543
Sometimes we identify with perceptions, swear that the earth was created in seven days, are ready to die for our belief.

96
00:09:33,686 --> 00:09:37,631
Then again, we can identify with character traits

97
00:09:38,118 --> 00:09:44,405
Perhaps we assume kindness or generosity are essential components of our true self.

98
00:09:44,426 --> 00:09:51,456
But this means we have to suppress any suggestions of unkindness or meanness, pretend they aren't happening.

99
00:09:52,256 --> 00:09:59,907
More harmfully, we can identify with negative characteristics like self-doubt, thinking I'm useless, I always make a mess of things.

100
00:10:01,253 --> 00:10:08,559
Though the identity is painful, it's also comforting as we never get disappointed because we never expect much of ourselves.

101
00:10:09,981 --> 00:10:26,518
The final aggregate is consciousness, where we assume our essence as the knowing of all our experience, thinking I am the one who sees and hears and smells and tastes and thinks and experiences the joys and pains of life.

102
00:10:27,697 --> 00:10:34,566
Buddha examined all of these areas but found all such identities to be inconstant, unreliable.

103
00:10:35,427 --> 00:10:45,260
Traits like generosity arose depending on conditions, feelings changed when circumstances changed, as did perceptions, and so on.

104
00:10:46,022 --> 00:10:52,730
None of these provided a stable foundation upon which he could declare, this is my true self.

105
00:10:53,772 --> 00:10:57,417
He also found that there was great pain, dukkha,

106
00:10:57,750 --> 00:11:01,416
in discovering each identity to be false.

107
00:11:01,436 --> 00:11:15,253
We cling vainly to our delusions, saying, I am feeling miserable, or I am useless, refusing to believe that these experiences come and go depending on conditions.

108
00:11:17,034 --> 00:11:25,985
The Buddha realised that peace came only when he relaxed all attempts to cling, to let go of any attempt to define himself.

109
00:11:27,417 --> 00:11:41,894
His teaching on anatta, not self, asks us to recognize that clinging to identity causes suffering, prevents us adapting to circumstances, flowing with life's vicissitudes.

110
00:11:41,913 --> 00:11:46,500
Note that the Buddha never denies that we have a self, an ultimate identity.

111
00:11:47,041 --> 00:11:57,373
He just says it cannot be defined or captured in any way that satisfies our craving for sense pleasure, our craving to be someone or to escape it all.

112
00:11:57,556 --> 00:11:58,256
be nobody.

113
00:11:59,298 --> 00:12:01,799
Any identity we find is temporary.

114
00:12:02,419 --> 00:12:04,081
It will eventually break up.

115
00:12:05,182 --> 00:12:09,025
But we can use every temporary identity wisely.

116
00:12:09,586 --> 00:12:15,572
He repeatedly asks us to look after our long-term happiness by practicing the Dhamma.

117
00:12:17,013 --> 00:12:27,241
We can have and encourage a healthy sense of self, so long as we know this as a friend on the path, a temporary gift, not our ultimate essence.

118
00:12:28,268 --> 00:12:35,378
In summary then, the first truth describes dukkha, tells us that we must fully understand dukkha.

119
00:12:35,398 --> 00:12:44,390
We can look for dukkha in any new beginning and in every ending, parting, saying goodbye when we're in sorrow, pain or despair.

120
00:12:44,792 --> 00:12:50,620
We can turn towards there as an opportunity to learn more about dukkha and its causes.

121
00:12:51,541 --> 00:12:58,191
Similarly, when we're getting over-identified by a role or job or believing this is me

122
00:12:58,475 --> 00:13:00,418
This is definitely not me.

123
00:13:01,240 --> 00:13:06,106
These are again perfect opportunities to study dukkha.

124
00:13:06,126 --> 00:13:11,034
The second truth the Buddha wants us to learn is what causes dukkha.

125
00:13:11,054 --> 00:13:15,341
We think that the problem lies with the world or other people or the laws of nature.

126
00:13:15,962 --> 00:13:19,850
But the Buddha discovered that the cause was within ourselves.

127
00:13:20,431 --> 00:13:24,297
Desire, tanha in Pali, caused him to suffer.

128
00:13:25,035 --> 00:13:30,822
Tanha includes what we usually call aversion, the desire to be rid of something.

129
00:13:32,043 --> 00:13:41,212
We suffer because we want more of the nice stuff, cakes and ale and rock and roll, praise, adulation, fame, beauty, health, youth.

130
00:13:41,932 --> 00:13:50,402
And when life gives us instead dry bread and blame and loneliness and old age, with its wrinkles and decrepitude, we don't know how to cope.

131
00:13:51,412 --> 00:13:59,461
The Buddha's wonderful discovery was that when he stopped wanting things to be anything other than the way they were, suffering also stopped.

132
00:13:59,481 --> 00:14:02,306
Even physical pain did not have to cause suffering.

133
00:14:02,826 --> 00:14:07,491
Once he accepted the pain, stopped making it a problem, suffering stopped.

134
00:14:07,511 --> 00:14:08,453
He was at peace.

135
00:14:09,394 --> 00:14:15,602
But as we all know, we can't command ourselves to accept pain or whatever other dukkha life is presenting.

136
00:14:16,443 --> 00:14:19,748
That would be to suppress dukkha, not to uproot it.

137
00:14:19,998 --> 00:14:24,803
Luckily, we have the capacity to learn that desire causes suffering.

138
00:14:25,804 --> 00:14:31,331
As that understanding sinks deeper, desire loses its grip.

139
00:14:31,351 --> 00:14:37,538
On the way, however, we have to learn to work skillfully with the many deluded desires that arise every day.

140
00:14:38,200 --> 00:14:40,081
For this, we have mindfulness.

141
00:14:40,743 --> 00:14:44,047
We watch ourselves longing vainly for things to be different.

142
00:14:44,868 --> 00:14:46,409
We're not suppressing desire.

143
00:14:46,677 --> 00:14:50,280
We're using the experience to learn the second known truth.

144
00:14:51,221 --> 00:14:53,445
Is desire really the cause of suffering?

145
00:14:54,044 --> 00:14:58,309
With this curiosity in mind, desire loses some of its edge.

146
00:14:59,611 --> 00:15:01,453
Say it was the desire for fame.

147
00:15:01,774 --> 00:15:08,981
We've been looking at Celebrity MasterChef and envying the winner, wanting everyone drooling over our crème caramel.

148
00:15:09,743 --> 00:15:14,489
If we turn away from the screen, use this opportunity to study Tamhac.

149
00:15:14,649 --> 00:15:15,570
We're halfway there.

150
00:15:16,207 --> 00:15:22,195
Desire might fade as soon as we spot it, and we realise how silly it was to be thinking that way.

151
00:15:23,535 --> 00:15:26,700
Other desires run too deep to stop on recognition.

152
00:15:27,461 --> 00:15:30,443
In that case, we feel the stresses and strains of longing.

153
00:15:31,144 --> 00:15:36,671
Watched mindfully, the desire at first grows very strong, but eventually burns out.

154
00:15:37,432 --> 00:15:44,139
The energy of desire usually drives thought and fantasies, which in turn feed that very desire.

155
00:15:44,929 --> 00:15:48,053
But now all that energy is contained by mindfulness.

156
00:15:48,693 --> 00:15:51,538
It's as if we've put ourselves into a pressure cooker.

157
00:15:52,099 --> 00:15:56,163
For a while, the energy might tense our jaws, our throat, our chest.

158
00:15:56,703 --> 00:15:59,226
We might be panting with unfulfilled desire.

159
00:15:59,727 --> 00:16:04,253
But after a while, desire exhausts itself, fades away.

160
00:16:05,053 --> 00:16:08,778
If we're lucky, we sense a moment of peace as desire fades.

161
00:16:09,479 --> 00:16:12,743
The absence of desire is a very beautiful experience.

162
00:16:13,043 --> 00:16:17,969
which the Buddha recognized as his third noble truth, the end of suffering.

163
00:16:19,129 --> 00:16:28,481
We're so lucky that the Buddha did the hard work of pinpointing this verse because otherwise few of us would take any notice of that moment of peace as desire fades.

164
00:16:29,363 --> 00:16:34,509
Unless we examine it, bring deliberate attention to it, peace is easily overlooked.

165
00:16:35,149 --> 00:16:36,511
It doesn't call attention.

166
00:16:36,812 --> 00:16:41,817
It's not a loud experience of joyous bliss that shouts, this is wonderful.

167
00:16:42,322 --> 00:16:44,504
It's simply the absence of any trouble.

168
00:16:45,807 --> 00:16:51,835
Our whole psychology and physiology is designed to be on alert for trouble and for enticement.

169
00:16:52,615 --> 00:16:54,437
It's part of our animal nature.

170
00:16:54,839 --> 00:17:02,568
We need to survive, so we have to be on the lookout for danger and also for food, shelter, our pals and whatever will help us survive.

171
00:17:03,210 --> 00:17:07,214
We're not biologically designed to make a big thing out of peace.

172
00:17:07,819 --> 00:17:19,270
That's why it's so easy for us to miss that brief moment when desire fades, to instead notice the next thing to grab our attention, then a new desire form around that.

173
00:17:20,192 --> 00:17:25,458
To sensitise ourselves to the third noble truth, we need to cultivate a taste for peace.

174
00:17:26,018 --> 00:17:36,949
Instead of booking one party after another, we spend some time in quietness, meditating perhaps, or walking in nature, sitting by the fire, listening to birdsong.

175
00:17:38,396 --> 00:17:40,900
This might not always feel so peaceful.

176
00:17:41,540 --> 00:17:48,028
We may have to combat our cultural conditioning to be always busy, always achieving something.

177
00:17:49,029 --> 00:17:52,953
So we might feel anxious or guilty sitting down doing nothing for an evening.

178
00:17:53,755 --> 00:17:57,359
Peace is actually not that easy to tolerate for long.

179
00:17:57,799 --> 00:18:03,606
The self, the me I presume myself to be, needs a role, a purpose.

180
00:18:03,626 --> 00:18:06,210
It wants to be getting something or getting somewhere.

181
00:18:06,595 --> 00:18:11,059
overcoming problems or doing good, affecting the world in some way.

182
00:18:12,320 --> 00:18:17,626
In perfect peace, there is nothing for me to do, no problems to solve.

183
00:18:17,646 --> 00:18:25,535
Most of us simply doze off after a minute or two, or else we grow restless, start to create problems just so we can solve them.

184
00:18:26,395 --> 00:18:29,779
What we're seeing here is the dukkha of identification.

185
00:18:30,299 --> 00:18:31,560
We want to be someone.

186
00:18:31,902 --> 00:18:32,942
We want definition.

187
00:18:33,584 --> 00:18:35,826
The self is born from reactivity.

188
00:18:36,176 --> 00:18:49,494
reacting against what we dislike, busily trying to get rid of it, reacting with desire for what we like, busy planning how to prolong the pleasure, get more of it, be someone important.

189
00:18:49,515 --> 00:19:05,998
To practice with the third noble truth, we can use any moments of peace wisely, let them be felt, knowledge, notice the tendency to burst out of it with some new identity and just keep relaxing all of that, telling ourselves it's fine to be redundant,

190
00:19:06,281 --> 00:19:12,768
To take it easy, have no role to play in life, quite a practice.

191
00:19:12,788 --> 00:19:17,952
Another way we can practice with the third truth is to start appreciating absences.

192
00:19:18,854 --> 00:19:25,780
We usually associate absence with grief, but rarely acknowledge that many absences are very beautiful.

193
00:19:26,362 --> 00:19:32,728
We easily notice pain, but we can also start to look out for parts of the body that are not in pain.

194
00:19:33,433 --> 00:19:39,319
The Buddha also advises us to notice when we're not angry, for example, not feeling greedy.

195
00:19:40,541 --> 00:19:47,689
When we're feeling uptight and frustrated, we can reflect that dullness and lethargy are absent.

196
00:19:47,709 --> 00:19:51,712
We can notice when others aren't imitating us or demanding anything.

197
00:19:52,614 --> 00:19:55,436
A retreat is an especially rich time for this.

198
00:19:56,137 --> 00:20:01,804
I used to think of my mother as very demanding, always asking me for something or other.

199
00:20:02,357 --> 00:20:09,930
It was quite an eye-opener to reflect that while I was on retreat, she was looking after herself, not putting me under any pressure.

200
00:20:10,631 --> 00:20:13,154
At first, I actually resisted the thought.

201
00:20:13,596 --> 00:20:18,042
My locked-in image of her as demanding was so strong it could not be budged.

202
00:20:18,884 --> 00:20:27,858
But gradually, I learned to acknowledge and be grateful for the fact that she was looking after herself quite well while I was away.

203
00:20:28,462 --> 00:20:33,107
I began to see her more realistically, admire and respect her strength of character.

204
00:20:33,709 --> 00:20:42,157
Our relationship improved and I'm very thankful that in her last years when she was more dependent on me, I didn't see this as a burden.

205
00:20:42,959 --> 00:20:47,263
Much of the time it was so easy and natural, I hardly thought about it at all.

206
00:20:48,325 --> 00:20:57,474
Something I had dreaded throughout much of my adult life turned out to be no problem and on the contrary, a source of quiet joy.

207
00:20:58,281 --> 00:21:07,715
If there is someone in your life who you see as oppressive in some way, it might really pay off to reflect that while you're here on the treat, they aren't oppressing you.

208
00:21:07,736 --> 00:21:12,182
We can also notice physical absences.

209
00:21:12,202 --> 00:21:20,736
When an ugly shed was demolished in this garden, the Dhamma teacher, Stephen Batchelor, spent days looking out the window, noticing the absence of the shed.

210
00:21:21,436 --> 00:21:26,365
In a similar way, we can notice that wherever we walk, there is space letting us pass through.

211
00:21:26,969 --> 00:21:31,233
We can look for the gaps between houses in the city, see the sky beyond.

212
00:21:31,273 --> 00:21:49,056
As we attune to space and absences and quiet, peaceful moments when life isn't troubling us, we deepen our understanding of the third noble truth, which the Buddha usually describes very simply as the end of suffering.

213
00:21:49,817 --> 00:21:54,241
To give a bit more flavour, we have these analogies from the monk Nagasena.

214
00:21:55,301 --> 00:22:25,308
Just as space is not produced, does not age, does not suffer death, cannot be carried away by thieves, rests on nothing, is the pathway of birds, presents no obstacles, is endless, so also nirvana is not produced, does not age, does not suffer, cannot be carried away by thieves, rests on nothing, is the pathway of the noble, presents no obstacles, is endless.

215
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:33,237
The great ocean is all in blossom with the flowers of waves, mighty, various, unnumbered.

216
00:22:34,258 --> 00:22:43,887
Precisely so, Nibbana is all in blossom with the flowers of purity, knowledge and deliverance, mighty, various and unnumbered.

217
00:22:45,209 --> 00:22:53,237
Even a brief taste of the peace that comes as desire fades will stir the skillful desire to find our way to Nibbana,

218
00:22:53,605 --> 00:23:00,334
which is exactly the concern of the fourth noble truth, known also as the noble eightfold path.

219
00:23:01,556 --> 00:23:13,472
I had been meditating for a while before it eventually sank in that meditation wasn't the whole of the spiritual life, that the eightfold path described many other areas of life that counted too.

220
00:23:14,354 --> 00:23:17,278
That gave me great joy and continues to do so.

221
00:23:17,798 --> 00:23:20,742
If I'm feeling glum and demotivated about work,

222
00:23:21,095 --> 00:23:26,541
I can reflect that my work is part of right livelihood, one of the strands of the Eightfold Path.

223
00:23:28,263 --> 00:23:32,829
That lifts my spirits, helps me to take on the work more willingly.

224
00:23:33,490 --> 00:23:39,738
Everything can be lifted from the dull and ordinary when we reflect that this is also leading towards liberation.

225
00:23:40,799 --> 00:23:48,269
The path is divided into three sections, wisdom, morality, and the cultivation of our mind and heart through meditation.

226
00:23:49,130 --> 00:23:50,612
Each of the eight strands

227
00:23:50,845 --> 00:23:55,392
It's described as right, right understanding, right attitude and so on.

228
00:23:56,094 --> 00:23:59,239
This can make the path seem like a set of rigid rules to follow.

229
00:23:59,819 --> 00:24:02,785
Disentangled is perhaps a better translation.

230
00:24:03,605 --> 00:24:07,031
It's a good description of what happens as we follow the path.

231
00:24:07,732 --> 00:24:12,601
We sense our thought processes straightening out, our emotional life disentangling.

232
00:24:13,040 --> 00:24:15,986
We become more straightforward in our dealings with others.

233
00:24:16,768 --> 00:24:17,628
In meditation,

234
00:24:17,895 --> 00:24:27,088
we can often feel ourselves getting into knots of tension as the hindrances show up and then feel the relief as those knots loosen in the light of awareness.

235
00:24:28,510 --> 00:24:37,201
Because disentangled is a bit of a mouthful, I'll follow the convention of calling each step right this or right that.

236
00:24:37,221 --> 00:24:44,932
But bear in mind the gentler and more evocative sense that we disentangle ourselves from the binds of dukkha as we develop our path.

237
00:24:46,262 --> 00:24:48,767
The first section is right understanding.

238
00:24:49,366 --> 00:24:55,115
We suffer because of not understanding what causes suffering and what prevents it.

239
00:24:55,135 --> 00:25:00,522
Reflecting on the Four Noble Truths starts us on the journey from delusion to wisdom.

240
00:25:01,183 --> 00:25:08,094
Experiencing these truths in moment-to-moment awareness lets them sink in deeply so that we take the Dhamma to heart.

241
00:25:08,815 --> 00:25:15,003
This naturally changes our attitude so that we become more kindly, generous, compassionate,

242
00:25:15,962 --> 00:25:21,569
This is what we mean by right attitude, the second strand to the eightfold palm.

243
00:25:22,672 --> 00:25:27,198
We can also cultivate right attitude by practicing metta meditation.

244
00:25:28,058 --> 00:25:31,963
Metta is usually translated as goodwill or loving kindness.

245
00:25:32,724 --> 00:25:35,709
We wish ourselves and others to be well and happy.

246
00:25:36,349 --> 00:25:38,592
This undermines habits like anger.

247
00:25:39,513 --> 00:25:45,902
In our gardening analogy, you could say it covers over the weeds, preventing them from getting any sunlight.

248
00:25:46,337 --> 00:25:49,261
They can't thrive and sow more seeds.

249
00:25:50,663 --> 00:25:59,997
When we feel our own pain or see that someone else is in physical or mental pain, the friendly attitude of Meta takes on the hue of compassion.

250
00:26:01,259 --> 00:26:09,329
We're sensitive to the suffering, careful not to make it any worse, ready to do whatever needs to be done to make things easier.

251
00:26:10,211 --> 00:26:14,336
At heart, we wish ourselves and others to be free from suffering.

252
00:26:15,515 --> 00:26:22,042
When something welcome happens, metta shades into mudita, often translated as a present of joy.

253
00:26:22,763 --> 00:26:24,586
We are gladdened by good news.

254
00:26:25,027 --> 00:26:29,613
We're ready to congratulate ourselves for any achievement, no matter how small.

255
00:26:30,173 --> 00:26:33,157
Even getting out of bed can be an achievement some days.

256
00:26:33,798 --> 00:26:37,282
When we hear of another's success, we feel happy for them.

257
00:26:38,404 --> 00:26:44,172
Metta cultivates friendliness, while compassion helps us bear suffering, and mudita

258
00:26:44,489 --> 00:26:46,672
lets us appreciate our many blessings.

259
00:26:47,693 --> 00:26:50,858
All of these need the support of equanimity.

260
00:26:51,920 --> 00:27:00,814
Without equanimity, meta easily overshoots into attachment and we become more dependent on our friends for our own sense of worth.

261
00:27:01,515 --> 00:27:07,984
With equanimity, we learn to accept that friends have separate lives, other responsibilities, other affections.

262
00:27:08,746 --> 00:27:12,791
Without the balance of equanimity, compassion slides into pity,

263
00:27:13,513 --> 00:27:17,519
We see ourselves as the stronger party, caring for the weaker one.

264
00:27:18,039 --> 00:27:20,803
It can become an addiction needing to be needed.

265
00:27:21,763 --> 00:27:27,611
Equanimity restores the balance, lets us see the strength at the core of the other's being.

266
00:27:28,873 --> 00:27:31,936
Mudita easily overshoots into excitement.

267
00:27:32,317 --> 00:27:34,680
We celebrate madly and go to excess.

268
00:27:35,040 --> 00:27:37,262
When the bills come in, we're shocked.

269
00:27:37,282 --> 00:27:41,107
Equanimity helps us recognize joy as a temporary gift.

270
00:27:41,611 --> 00:27:44,894
while knowing that all earthly joys are bound to fade.

271
00:27:46,875 --> 00:27:50,700
The Meta Sutta is a beautiful description of right attitude.

272
00:27:51,220 --> 00:27:53,301
We chant this every morning in Pali.

273
00:27:53,863 --> 00:28:03,892
Here's an English translation read by Mark Arthur, another teacher here at Satipaña.

274
00:28:03,912 --> 00:28:08,817
So this is what should be done by one who was skilled in goodness.

275
00:28:10,315 --> 00:28:11,876
and who knows the path of peace.

276
00:28:13,700 --> 00:28:40,238
Let them be able and upright, straightforward and gentle in speech, humble and not conceited, contented and easily satisfied, unburdened with duties and frugal in their ways, peaceful and calm and wise and skillful, not proud or demanding in nature,

277
00:28:41,550 --> 00:28:46,666
Let them not do the slightest thing that the wise would later reprove.

278
00:28:48,372 --> 00:28:54,108
Wishing, in gladness and in safety, may all beings be at ease.

279
00:28:55,557 --> 00:29:17,391
Whatever living beings there may be, whether they are weak or strong, omitting none, the great or the mighty, medium, short or small, the seen and the unseen, those living near and far away, those born and to be born, may all beings be at ease.

280
00:29:19,394 --> 00:29:23,099
Let none deceive another or despise any being in any state.

281
00:29:24,025 --> 00:29:27,628
let none through anger or ill will wish harm upon another.

282
00:29:29,111 --> 00:29:48,192
Even as a mother protects with her life a child, her only child, so with a boundless heart should one cherish all living beings, radiating kindness over the entire world, spreading upwards to the skies and downwards to the depths.

283
00:29:49,861 --> 00:29:54,547
outwards and unbounded, freed from hatred and ill-will.

284
00:29:56,509 --> 00:30:04,578
Whether standing or walking, seated or lying down, free from drowsiness, one should sustain this recollection.

285
00:30:06,121 --> 00:30:08,644
This is said to be the sublime abiding.

286
00:30:11,086 --> 00:30:19,597
And by not holding to fixed views, the pure-hearted one, having clarity of vision, being freed from all sense desires,

287
00:30:20,454 --> 00:30:23,217
is not born again into this world.

288
00:30:30,384 --> 00:30:37,450
Right understanding and right attitude combine as wisdom, the first section of the Eightfold Path.

289
00:30:37,470 --> 00:30:44,115
The next section, termed Sila in Pali, concerns the expression of wisdom in daily life.

290
00:30:45,396 --> 00:30:48,960
Sila is usually translated as morality or ethics.

291
00:30:49,700 --> 00:30:56,689
I'm going to use the Pally word sila because we often associate morality with a strict, joyless approach to life.

292
00:30:57,450 --> 00:31:00,433
Family photos from Victorian times illustrate this.

293
00:31:00,914 --> 00:31:01,756
No one smiles.

294
00:31:02,195 --> 00:31:05,119
The children look miserable in their heavy, awkward clothes.

295
00:31:05,721 --> 00:31:15,753
An austere father towers over them while his wife sits demurely at his side, laced and buttoned to within an inch of her life.

296
00:31:15,773 --> 00:31:18,998
Desire finds no expression in this picture of morality.

297
00:31:20,159 --> 00:31:23,761
But we need to remember that desire can also be wise.

298
00:31:24,262 --> 00:31:28,026
The desire to be happy is perhaps our most basic drive in life.

299
00:31:28,606 --> 00:31:36,113
It only gets us into trouble because we don't rightly understand what allows for happiness, what causes suffering.

300
00:31:36,133 --> 00:31:41,738
The Buddha promises us that if we follow this path, we will be content and therefore happy.

301
00:31:42,499 --> 00:31:46,442
Morality in this life is seen as a step toward happiness.

302
00:31:47,022 --> 00:31:48,984
Zila is not an easy matter.

303
00:31:49,623 --> 00:31:55,212
For each of us, there will be difficult ethical questions to face at many stages in life.

304
00:31:55,973 --> 00:32:04,470
We need a clear mind to find the appropriate response in complex situations, along with a stout heart to meet the challenge.

305
00:32:05,290 --> 00:32:10,780
We also need to be patient with our many mistakes, not torment ourselves about them.

306
00:32:11,422 --> 00:32:14,247
But remember, we can learn to do better.

307
00:32:17,585 --> 00:32:24,070
The Buddha divides Sila into three sections, right speech, right action and right livelihood.

308
00:32:24,791 --> 00:32:31,838
Here are three areas of life where we can tailor our behaviour so as to promote our own long-term happiness.

309
00:32:32,598 --> 00:32:39,165
Tomorrow's talk is on daily life and as Sila is so relevant to this, I won't discuss it further here.

310
00:32:39,965 --> 00:32:45,971
Tomorrow I'll give suggestions as to how we can develop Sila as we go about our everyday business.

311
00:32:46,828 --> 00:32:53,115
The last section of the Eightfold Path concerns the cultivation of mind and heart in meditation practice.

312
00:32:53,935 --> 00:32:58,579
And as we've been engaged in this all week, I'll only briefly mention it here.

313
00:32:58,621 --> 00:33:06,728
The Buddha describes three aspects to cultivate, right effort, mindfulness, and concentration.

314
00:33:07,648 --> 00:33:15,537
So here we have again, the leading trio in our wild geese, mindfulness, energy, concentration.

315
00:33:16,394 --> 00:33:22,701
To see their interrelation, we have the analogy of three children wanting to pick fruit from a tree.

316
00:33:23,541 --> 00:33:40,142
None of them is tall enough to reach the fruit, so the strongest one, right effort, bends over to let the tallest one, right concentration, stand on his back while the steadiest of the three, right mindfulness, provides a shoulder to lean on.

317
00:33:40,942 --> 00:33:44,747
Supported by right effort, balanced by mindfulness,

318
00:33:45,097 --> 00:33:48,080
Concentration can then pluck the fruit.

319
00:33:50,323 --> 00:34:02,655
Again, I'll say more about this and all aspects of the Eightfold Path tomorrow as we look at how we can maintain and strengthen our meditation practice in daily life.

320
00:34:02,675 --> 00:34:07,800
In summary, the Four Noble Truths concern Dukkha and how to bring it to an end.

321
00:34:08,422 --> 00:34:13,586
The Buddha said that his own liberation came from fully understanding Dukkha,

322
00:34:13,987 --> 00:34:16,271
from seeing that desire was the cause.

323
00:34:17,072 --> 00:34:22,858
As he let go of desire, he realized that dukkha came to an end, simply stopped happening.

324
00:34:23,880 --> 00:34:31,489
To bring it to a permanent close, he followed the Eightfold Path.

325
00:34:31,509 --> 00:34:39,938
Lost in the jungle of ignorance, we ponder the Four Noble Truths to get an inkling of what causes suffering and what relieves it.

326
00:34:40,659 --> 00:34:42,021
As the truth sinks in,

327
00:34:42,355 --> 00:34:44,157
our attitude grows friendlier.

328
00:34:44,797 --> 00:34:49,322
The sword of wisdom cuts through some tangles of delusion to form a clearing.

329
00:34:50,103 --> 00:34:59,135
Sila blossoms in the form of right speech, action and livelihood to be rewarded by the law of karma so that we become happier.

330
00:35:00,115 --> 00:35:07,905
The jungle no longer seems so threatening and we rest a while in the clearing to cultivate our mind and heart in meditation.

331
00:35:08,826 --> 00:35:10,168
Supported by effort,

332
00:35:10,603 --> 00:35:18,735
Led and balanced by mindfulness, our mind focuses on the diamond and the four noble truths sink in even deeper.

333
00:35:20,378 --> 00:35:25,545
This sharpens the sword of wisdom, which cuts through another thicket of delusion.

334
00:35:26,527 --> 00:35:36,242
Step by step, we form the path that leads from the jungle of ignorance to the freedom of enlightenment.

335
00:35:36,262 --> 00:35:38,585
In what is termed his victory verse,

336
00:35:39,106 --> 00:35:50,000
The Buddha uses the analogy of a house builder to describe the delusive desire, tanha, that drives us to seek our essence within the world, build castles in the air.

337
00:35:51,141 --> 00:35:57,530
The rich pole for these castles is ignorance, our lack of understanding about dukkha and its cause.

338
00:35:58,931 --> 00:36:01,175
Here is the Buddha's victory birth.

339
00:36:02,556 --> 00:36:08,403
Seeking but not finding the house builder, I have travelled through the round of countless births,

340
00:36:09,295 --> 00:36:12,498
How painful is birth over and over again.

341
00:36:12,559 --> 00:36:16,322
Oh house builder, you have now been caught.

342
00:36:16,943 --> 00:36:18,804
You shall not build a house again.

343
00:36:19,485 --> 00:36:21,208
Your rafters have been broken.

344
00:36:21,688 --> 00:36:23,190
Your rich pole demolished.

345
00:36:24,010 --> 00:36:31,039
The unconditioned consciousness has been attained and every kind of craving has been destroyed.

346
00:36:34,181 --> 00:36:38,306
I hope this overview of the Four Noble Truths has been helpful.

347
00:36:40,597 --> 00:36:44,262
May all beings come to the end of suffering.

